# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ultrasound-imaging
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ultrasound-imaging/acoustic-impedance] Acoustic resistance represents the energy transfer of an acoustic wave.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/acoustic-impedance] The pressure and motion are in phase, so work is done on the medium ahead of the wave.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/acoustic-impedance] Acoustic reactance represents the pressure that is out of phase with the motion and causes no average energy transfer.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/acoustic-impedance] For example, a closed bulb connected to an organ pipe will have air moving into it and pressure, but they are out of phase, so no net energy is transmitted into it.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/acoustic-impedance] While the pressure rises, air moves in, and while it falls, it moves out, but the average pressure when the air moves in is the same as that when it moves out, so the power flows back and forth but with no time-averaged energy transfer.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/acoustic-impedance] A further electrical analogy is a capacitor connected across a power line: current flows through the capacitor but it is out of phase with the voltage, so no net power is transmitted into it.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/acoustic-impedance] where *v*−1 is the convolution inverse of *v*.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/acoustic-impedance] The **acoustic ohm** is a unit of measurement of acoustic impedance.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/acoustic-impedance] The SI unit of pressure is the pascal and of flow is cubic metres per second, so the acoustic ohm is equal to 1 Pa·s/m3.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/acoustic-impedance] The acoustic ohm can be applied to fluid flow outside the domain of acoustics.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/acoustic-impedance] For such applications, a **hydraulic ohm** with an identical definition may be used.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/acoustic-impedance] A hydraulic ohm measurement would be the ratio of hydraulic pressure to hydraulic volume flow.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/acoustic-impedance] This equation is valid both for fluids and solids.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/acoustic-impedance] Temperature acts on speed of sound and mass density and thus on specific acoustic impedance.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] Duplex ultrasonography sometimes refers to Doppler ultrasonography or spectral Doppler ultrasonography.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] Doppler ultrasonography consists of two components: brightness mode (B-mode) showing anatomy of the organs, and Doppler mode (showing blood flow) superimposed on the B-mode.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] Meanwhile, spectral Doppler ultrasonography consists of three components: B-mode, Doppler mode, and spectral waveform displayed at the lower half of the image.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] Therefore, "duplex ultrasonography" is a misnomer for spectral Doppler ultrasonography, and more exact name should be "triplex ultrasonography".
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] This is particularly useful in cardiovascular studies (sonography of the vascular system and heart) and essential in many areas such as determining reverse blood flow in the liver vasculature in portal hypertension.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] Colour Doppler shows the direction of the blood flow in red or blue (either towards or away from the transducer).
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] Meanwhile, spectral Doppler not only shows the direction of blood flow, it also shows the phases (pulsatility) and acceleration of the blood flow.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] Any sudden changes in direction of blood flow produces audible sounds on the ultrasound machine.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] In spectral Doppler, the y-axis shows the direction and velocity of the flow.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] Meanwhile, the x-axis (as known as "baseline") shows the flow over time.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] The gradient at any point on the waveform would therefore shows the acceleration of the flow.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] In "antegrade" flow, the blood flows according to the normal flow within the circulatory system (e.g. veins flow towards the heart while arteries flows away from the heart).
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] In "retrograde" flow, the flow would reverse (e.g. veins flow away from heart or arteries flow towards the heart).
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] However, "retrograde" flow can be both abnormal or normal.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] For example, in portal hypertension, there is an abnormal portal venous flow where it flows away from the liver (hepatofugal flow) instead of the normal flow towards liver (hepatopetal flow).
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] In jugular venous pressure waveform of the internal jugular vein, the retrograde "a" waveform is a normal flow due to right atrium contraction.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] Both antegrade or retrograde flow can be either towards or away from the probe transducer, depending on the position of the probe relative to the blood flow.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] Blood flow toward the transducer would appear above the baseline while blood flows away from the transducer will appear below the baseline.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] Waveform of the flow can be classified as: pulsatile (as in arteries), phasic (as in veins), non-phasic (as in diseased veins), and aphasic (no flow).
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] Spectral broadening (thickness of the waveform) increases from large vessels (plug flow) to medium vessels (laminar flow) to small/stenotic/diseased vessels (turbulent flow) due to a larger variety of blood with different ranges of velocities in those with turbulent flow.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] Upstream and downstream stenosis refers to the location of the stenotic site relative to the ultrasound probe.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] Upstream stenosis means the location of stenosis is located before the ultrasound probe.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] It causes a marked decrease in peak systolic velocity when compared to end-diastolic velocity, causing marked reduction in resistance index.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] Meanwhile, downstream stenosis is located after the ultrasound probe.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] Thus, there is only a slight reduction in peak systolic velocity and end-diastolic velocity (where end-diastolic velocity is reduced more than peak systolic velocity), resulting in an increased resistance index.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] Power Doppler is a non directional Doppler.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] All modern ultrasound scanners use pulsed Doppler to measure velocity.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] Pulsed wave instruments transmit and receive series of pulses.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] The frequency shift of each pulse is ignored, however the relative phase changes of the pulses are used to obtain the frequency shift (since frequency is the rate of change of phase).
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] The major advantage of pulsed wave Doppler (PW Doppler) over continuous wave (CW Doppler) is that distance information is obtained (time between transmitted and received pulses multiplied by sound velocity equals distance) and gain correction is applied.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] The disadvantage of pulsed Doppler is that the measurements can suffer from aliasing.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] The terms *Doppler ultrasound* and *Doppler sonography* have been accepted to apply to both pulsed and continuous Doppler systems, despite the different mechanisms by which the velocity is measured.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] There are no standards for displaying color Doppler.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] Some laboratories show arteries as red and veins as blue, as medical illustrators usually show them, even though some vessels may have portions flowing toward and portions flowing away from the transducer.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] This results in the illogical appearance of a vessel being partly a vein and partly an artery.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] Other laboratories use red to indicate flow toward the transducer and blue away from the transducer.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] Still other laboratories display the Doppler color map in accordance with published data, with red shift representing longer wavelengths (scattered) from blood flowing away from the transducer and blue representing the shorter wavelengths from blood flowing toward the transducer.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] Because of this confusion and lack of standards, the sonographer must understand the underlying physics of color Doppler and the physiology of normal and abnormal blood flow in the human body (see Red shift).
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] Transcranial Doppler (TCD) and transcranial colour Doppler (TCCD) measure the velocity of blood flow through the brain's blood vessels transcranially (through the cranium).
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] These modes of medical imaging conduct a spectral analysis of the acoustic signals they receive and can therefore be classified as methods of active acoustocerebrography.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] They are used as tests to help diagnose emboli, stenosis, vasospasm from a subarachnoid hemorrhage (bleeding from a ruptured aneurysm), and other problems.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] These relatively quick and inexpensive tests are growing in popularity.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] The tests are effective for detecting sickle cell disease, ischemic cerebrovascular disease, subarachnoid hemorrhage, arteriovenous malformations, and cerebral circulatory arrest.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] The tests are possibly useful for perioperative monitoring and meningeal infection.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] The equipment used for these tests is becoming increasingly portable, making it possible for a clinician to travel to a hospital, to a doctor's office, or to a nursing home for both inpatient and outpatient studies.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] The tests are often used in conjunction with other tests such as MRI, MRA, carotid duplex ultrasound and CT scans.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] The tests are also used for research in cognitive neuroscience.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] Vascular ultrasonography helps determine multiple factors within the circulatory system.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] It can evaluate central (abdominal) and peripheral arteries and veins, it helps determine the amount of vascular stenosis (narrowing) or occlusion (complete blockage) within an artery, it assists in ruling out aneurysmal disease, and it is the main aid to rule out thrombotic events.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] Duplex is an inexpensive, non-invasive way to determine pathology.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] Duplex evaluation is usually done prior to any invasive testing or surgical procedure.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] Ultrasound duplex scanning can provide additional information that may guide therapeutic decisions.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] The location and severity of arterial narrowings and occlusions can be identified.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] The vascular sonographer can map disease in lower-extremity segments with great accuracy, though duplex scanning is more time-consuming than other lower-extremity arterial studies.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] An alternative to Doppler to visualize vessels is B-flow, which digitally highlights weak flow reflectors (mainly red blood cells) while suppressing the signals from the surrounding stationary tissue.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] It can visualize flowing blood and surrounding stationary tissues simultaneously.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] It also can monitor the pulse of blood vessels via doppler pulse detection.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] In addition to visualization, ultrasound can also be used in Doppler auscultation (without visual), similar to using an ultrasound baby monitor, to locate clots or other vascular obstructions or collapse by tracing a blood vessel until sound is no longer heard.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] It is also used to confirm patency of dorsalis pedis arteries when edema or other conditions make manual palpation impractical.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] Doppler ultrasonography is widely used in renal ultrasonography.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] Renal vessels are easily depicted by the color Doppler technique in order to evaluate perfusion.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] Doppler echocardiography is the use of Doppler ultrasonography to examine the heart.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] An echocardiogram can, within certain limits, produce an accurate assessment of the direction of blood flow and the velocity of blood and cardiac tissue at any arbitrary point using the Doppler effect.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] One of the limitations is that the ultrasound beam should be as parallel to the blood flow as possible.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] Contrast-enhanced ultrasound using gas-filled microbubble contrast media can be used to improve velocity or other flow-related medical measurements.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] Doppler fetal monitors, although usually not technically -graphy but rather sound-generating, use the Doppler effect to detect the fetal heartbeat for prenatal care.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] These are hand-held, and some models also display the heart rate in beats per minute (BPM).
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] Use of this monitor is sometimes known as *Doppler auscultation*.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] The Doppler fetal monitor is commonly referred to simply as a *Doppler* or *fetal Doppler*.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] Doppler fetal monitors provide information about the fetus similar to that provided by a fetal stethoscope.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] Doppler ultrasonography can help distinguishing benign from malignant soft tissue lumps.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/doppler-ultrasonography] Power Doppler is useful in assessing tendon and joints inflammation such as paratenonitis.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] Echocardiography is routinely used in the diagnosis, management, and follow-up of patients with any suspected or known heart diseases.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] It is one of the most widely used diagnostic imaging modalities in cardiology.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] It can provide a wealth of helpful information, including the size and shape of the heart (internal chamber size quantification), pumping capacity, location and extent of any tissue damage, and assessment of valves.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] An echocardiogram can also give physicians other estimates of heart function, such as a calculation of the cardiac output, ejection fraction, and diastolic function (how well the heart relaxes).
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] Echocardiography is an important tool in assessing wall motion abnormality in patients with suspected cardiac disease.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] It is a tool which helps in reaching an early diagnosis of myocardial infarction, showing regional wall motion abnormality.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] Also, it is important in treatment and follow-up in patients with heart failure, by assessing ejection fraction.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] Echocardiography can help detect cardiomyopathies, such as hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, and dilated cardiomyopathy.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] The use of stress echocardiography may also help determine whether any chest pain or associated symptoms are related to heart disease.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] The most important advantages of echocardiography are that it is not invasive (does not involve breaking the skin or entering body cavities) and has no known risks or side effects.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] Not only can an echocardiogram create ultrasound images of heart structures, but it can also produce accurate assessment of the blood flowing through the heart by Doppler echocardiography, using pulsed- or continuous-wave Doppler ultrasound.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] This allows assessment of both normal and abnormal blood flow through the heart.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] The Doppler technique can also be used for tissue motion and velocity measurement, by tissue Doppler echocardiography.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] Echocardiography was also the first ultrasound subspecialty to use intravenous contrast.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] Echocardiography is performed by cardiac sonographers, cardiac physiologists (UK), or physicians trained in echocardiography.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] The Swedish physician Inge Edler (1911–2001), a graduate of Lund University, is recognized as the "Father of Echocardiography".
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] He was the first in his profession to apply ultrasonic pulse echo imaging, which the acoustical physicist Floyd Firestone had developed to detect defects in metal castings, in diagnosing cardiac disease.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] Edler in 1953 produced the first echocardiographs using an industrial Firestone-Sperry Ultrasonic Reflectoscope.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] In developing echocardiography, Edler worked with the physicist Carl Hellmuth Hertz, the son of the Nobel laureate Gustav Hertz and grandnephew of Heinrich Rudolph Hertz.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] Health societies recommend the use of echocardiography for initial diagnosis when a change in the person's clinical status occurs and when new data from an echocardiogram would result in the physician changing the person's care.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] Diagnostic criteria for numerous cardiac diseases are based on echocardiography studies.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] For example, the differentiation of mild, moderate, and severe valvular disease is based upon measured criteria.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] Another example is the estimation of heart function by the left ventricular ejection fraction (LVEF) has vast uses including classification of heart failure and cut offs for implantation of implantable cardioverter-defibrillators.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] Health societies do not recommend routine testing when the patient has no change in clinical status or when a physician is unlikely to change care for the patient based on the results of testing.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] A common example of overuse of echocardiography when not indicated is the use of routine testing in response to a patient diagnosis of mild valvular heart disease.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] In this case, patients are often asymptomatic for years before the onset of deterioration and the results of the echocardiogram would not result in a change in care without other change in clinical status.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] Echocardiography has a vast role in pediatrics, diagnosing patients with valvular heart disease and other congenital abnormalities.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] An emerging branch is fetal echocardiography, which involves echocardiography of an unborn fetus.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] A standard echocardiogram is also known as a transthoracic echocardiogram (TTE) or cardiac ultrasound, and it is used for rapid evaluation of a patient at their bedside.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] In this case, ultrasound gel is applied to the chest wall to help transmitt the ultrasound waves, then the echocardiography transducer (or probe) is placed on the chest wall (or thorax) of the subject, and images are taken through the chest wall.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] This is a non-invasive, highly accurate, and quick assessment of the overall function of the heart.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] Transthoracic echocardiography can display structure of heart chambers, myocardial motion, and valvular function in real time, and is widely used to access a variety of cardiovascular diseases, such as ventricular systolic dysfunction, valvular heart disease, and pericardial disease.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] But, although TTE is a non-invasive and widely used examination method, its image quality can be influenced by body fat, thickness of chest, and other factors.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] TTE utilizes several "windows" to image the heart from different perspectives.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] Each window has advantages and disadvantages for viewing specific structures within the heart and, typically, numerous windows are utilized within the same study to fully assess the heart.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] Parasternal long and parasternal short axis windows are taken next to the sternum, the apical two/three/four chamber windows are taken from the apex of the heart (lower left side), and the subcostal window is taken from underneath the edge of the last rib.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] TTE utilizes M-mode, 2D and 3D ultrasounds (time is implicit and not included) from the different windows.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] These can be combined with pulse wave or continuous wave Doppler to visualize the velocity of blood flow through the left ventricle and structure movements.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] Images can be enhanced with "contrast" that are typically some sort of micro bubble suspension that reflect the ultrasound waves.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] A transesophageal echocardiogram is an alternative way to perform an echocardiogram.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] A specialized probe containing an ultrasound transducer at its tip is passed into the patient's esophagus via the mouth, allowing image and Doppler evaluation from a location directly behind the heart.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] It is most often used when transthoracic images are suboptimal and when a clearer and more precise image is needed for assessment or in specific conditions such as being in a critical condition, such as having low oxygen levels or needing heart surgery.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] Because the esophagus is located behind and close to the heart, this method can provide higher resolution images than Transthoracic echocardiography (TTE).
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] This test is performed in the presence of a cardiologist, anesthesiologist, registered nurse, and ultrasound technologist.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] During the examination, patients need to be fasting.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] Before the examination begins, the doctor will administer local anesthesia to patient's throat and administer sedative drugs if necessary.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] During the examination, a flexible scope with an ultrasound probe will be slowly inserted into the esophagus, the position and angle of the probe can be adjusted as needed to obtain different angle of view.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] Additionally, modern multiplane TEE probes use transducer elements to generate a two-dimension plane, and the ultrasound plane can be rotated electronically to permit an additional dimension to optimize views of the heart structures.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] Often, movement in all of these dimensions is needed.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] TEE can be used as stand-alone procedures, or incorporated into catheter- or surgical-based procedures.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] For example, during a valve replacement surgery the TEE can be used to assess the valve function immediately before repair/replacement and immediately after.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] This permits revising the valve mid-surgery, if needed, to improve outcomes of the surgery.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] A stress echocardiogram, also known as a stress echo, uses ultrasound imaging of the heart to assess the wall motion in response to physical stress.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] First, images of the heart are taken "at rest" to acquire a baseline of the patient's wall motion at a resting heart rate.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] The patient then walks on a treadmill or uses another exercise modality to increase the heart rate to his or her target heart rate, or 85% of the age-predicted maximum heart rate (220 − patient's age).
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] Finally, images of the heart are taken "at stress" to assess wall motion at the peak heart rate.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] A stress echo assesses wall motion of the heart; it does not, however, create an image of the coronary arteries directly.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] Ischemia of one or more coronary arteries could cause a wall motion abnormality, which could indicate coronary artery disease.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] The gold standard test to directly create an image of the coronary arteries and directly assess for stenosis or occlusion is a cardiac catheterization.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] A stress echo is not invasive and is performed in the presence of a licensed medical professional, such as a cardiologist, and a cardiac sonographer.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] A systematic review and meta-analysis published in Heart in 2024 studied the long-term capabilities of stress echocardiography being used to identify coronary artery disease.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] Data were collected from over 16,000 patients from a total of six clinical trials.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] The results from the meta-analysis show that patients with a positive stress echocardiography test (indicative of reduced blood flow to the heart from coronary arteries) had higher annual rates of major adverse cardiovascular events (MACE) and all-cause mortality than those with negative results.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] The annual MACE rate was 1.99% for patients with a positive test compared to 1.54% in those with negative tests.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] The mortality rates for the patients were 1.68% and 1.02% respectively.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] The results from the meta-analysis show that stress echocardiography may be able to provide predictive long-term information and can be used for better risk assessment in patients with coronary artery disease.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] Intracardiac echocardiography (ICE) is specialized form of echocardiography that uses catheters to insert the ultrasound probe inside the heart to view structures from within the heart.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] ICE has the benefit over transthoracic echocardiography in that an operator who is performing a sterile procedure can also operate the ICE catheter and it is not limited to visibility problems that can arise with transthoracic or transesophageal echo.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] Though, there are image quality limitations due to size constraints of the probe being limited to a catheter.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] ICE is often inserted through the femoral vein and into the right atrium.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] From the right atrium, visualization of the interatrial septum, all four cardiac chambers, all four valves, and the pericardial space (for an effusion) can be readily visualized.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] It can also be advanced across the atrial septum into the left atrium to visualize the left atrial appendage during left atrial appendage occlusion device deployment.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] According to Singleton & Osorio Electrophysiologic studies and catheter ablation have been done using fluoroscopic guidance but have recently transitioned to using electroanatomic mapping (EAM) and ICE to stop using fluoroscopy.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] EAM and ICE allow for three-dimensional accurate images of the chamber being imaged, guidewires, and catheter-tissue interfaces.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] This combination has replaced fluoroscopy for electrophysiologic procedures.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] Intravascular ultrasound (IVUS) is an intravascular technique that uses a catheter to insert the ultrasound probe inside blood vessels.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] This is commonly used to measure the size of blood vessels and to measure the internal diameter of the blood vessel.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] For example, this can be used in a coronary angiogram to assess the narrowing of the coronary artery.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] IVUS images the inside of blood vessels, so it allowed direct observation of the inside of vessels.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] During the examination, a catheter with ultrasound probe is inserted into a blood vessel through the femoral or radial artery.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] Then the probe can be pushed to the target vessel location, such as coronary artery.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] When probe reached, it emits ultrasound waves and received reflected echoes.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] As the catheter is retraced in a controlled manner, then an internal map can be generated to see the contour of the vessel and its branches.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] The various modes describe how the ultrasound crystals are used to obtain information.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] These modes are common to all types of echocardiography.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] A-scan or one-dimensional ultrasound represents over half the standard ECHO exam.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] The A stands for amplitude which means the echocardiogram is the processed amplitude versus time produced as an output from the receiver of ultrasound.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] For example, it is how aortic stenosis valve area (or any obstruction).
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] It is also how pressures are calculated in the heart such as right ventricle systolic pressure (RVSP).
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] It is usually used in the form of Doppler measurements.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] There are two forms, pulse and continuous.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] Pulsed allows velocities to be calculated in a specific place but has a limited velocity range can be used.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] Continuous wave allows the velocity to be measured from zero to the fastest blood velocities a diseased heart can generate.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] However, it cannot tell you where in the A-scan the high velocity is coming from.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] Continuous wave would be used to calculate aortic stenosis because you know the high velocity is coming from the stenosis region.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] Pulsed would be used to find a ventricular septal defect where there should be no velocity across the septum and the pulsed tells you the location.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] B-mode is also known as brightness mode.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] It is based on the conversion of A-mode ultrasound signals into a two-dimensional grayscale image, where stronger signal appear brighter and weaker signals appear darker.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] Multiple signal lines swept across the heart can build a cross-sectional image of it in real time.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] M-Mode uses a single ultrasound line to obtain a one-dimensional view of all the structures that reflect the ultrasound wave.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] The ultrasounds in M-mode can capture the heart in systole and diastole.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] One disadvantage of M-mode is that it only uses one ultrasound line which is not able to move from the tip of the transducer.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] Strain rate imaging utilizing echocardiography is a method that can be used to detect abnormalities in the heart.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] Strain rate imaging measures either regional systolic deformation (strain) or the rate of regional deformation (strain rate).
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] The methods used are either tissue Doppler or Speckle tracking echocardiography.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] (2024) one clinical application of strain rate imaging is using longitudinal strain instead of using ejection fraction for diagnosing mild systolic dysfunction.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] Three-dimensional echocardiography (also known as four-dimensional echocardiography when the picture is moving) is possible using a matrix array ultrasound probe and an appropriate processing system.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] It enables detailed anatomical assessment of cardiac pathology, particularly valvular defects, and cardiomyopathies.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] The ability to slice the virtual heart in infinite planes in an anatomically appropriate manner and to reconstruct three-dimensional images of anatomic structures make it unique for the understanding of the congenitally malformed heart.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] Real-time three-dimensional echocardiography can be used to guide the location of bioptomes during right ventricular endomyocardial biopsies, placement of catheter-delivered valvular devices, and in many other intraoperative assessments.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] Three-dimensional echocardiography technology may feature anatomical intelligence, or the use of organ-modeling technology, to automatically identify anatomy based on generic models.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] All generic models refer to a dataset of anatomical information that uniquely adapts to variability in patient anatomy to perform specific tasks.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] Built on feature recognition and segmentation algorithms, this technology can provide patient-specific three-dimensional modeling of the heart and other aspects of the anatomy, including the brain, lungs, liver, kidneys, rib cage, and vertebral column.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] Myocardial Contrast Echocardiography (MCE) is a technique that has been developed over the past three decades that uses microbubbles, also called ultrasound-enhancing agents (UEA) to improve cardiac imaging.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] UEA improves signal acquisition (increased backscatter) and amplifies the signal (non-linear behavior) which helps improve tissue contrast of the heart and detect abnormalities.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] The microbubbles are smaller than 10 μm so they do not disrupt any blood vessels.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] UEA's have shown to be safe and effective in identifying various cardiac diseases.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] It necessitated the development of accreditation programs around the world.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] The aim of such programs is to standardize the practice of echocardiography and to ensure that practitioners have the proper training prior to practicing echocardiography which will eventually limit inter-observer variability.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] At the European level individual and laboratory accreditation is provided by the European Association of Echocardiography (EAE).
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] There are three subspecialties for individual accreditation: Adult Transthoracic Echocardiography (**TTE**), Adult Transesophageal Echocardiography (**TEE**) and Congenital Heart Disease Echocardiography (CHD).
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] In the UK, accreditation is regulated by the British Society of Echocardiography.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] Accredited radiographers, sonographers, or other professionals are required to pass a mandatory exam.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] The "Intersocietal Accreditation Commission for Echocardiography" (IAC) sets standards for echo labs across the US.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] Cardiologists and sonographers who wish to have their laboratory accredited by IAC must comply with these standards.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] The purpose of accreditation is to maintain quality and consistency across echocardiography labs in the United States.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] Accreditation is offered in adult and pediatric transthoracic and transesophageal echocardiography, as well as adult stress and fetal echo.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] Each facility will conduct a detailed self-evaluation, paying close attention to the IAC Standards and Guidelines.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] The facility will then complete the application and submit actual case studies to the board of directors for review.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] Once all requirements have been met, the lab will receive certification.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] IAC certification is a continual process and must be maintained by the facility: it may include audits or site visits by the IAC.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] There are several states in which Medicare and/or private insurance carriers require accreditation (credentials) of the laboratory and/or sonographer for reimbursement of echocardiograms.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] There are two credentialing bodies in the United States for sonographers, the *Cardiovascular Credentialing International* (CCI), established in 1968, and the *American Registry for Diagnostic Medical Sonography* (ARDMS), established in 1975.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] Both CCI and ARDMS have earned the prestigious *ANSI-ISO 17024* accreditation for certifying bodies from the International Organization for Standardization (*ISO*).
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] Accreditation is granted through the American National Standards Institute (ANSI).
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] Recognition of ARDMS programs in providing credentials has also earned the ARDMS accreditation with the National Commission for Certifying Agencies (NCCA).
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] The NCCA is the accrediting arm of the National Organization for Competency Assurance (NOCA).
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] Under both credentialing bodies, sonographers must first document completion of prerequisite requirements, which contain both didactic and hands-on experience in the field of ultrasound.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] Applicants must then take a comprehensive exam demonstrating knowledge in both the physics of ultrasound and the clinical competency related to their specialty.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] Credentialed sonographers are then required to maintain competency in their field by obtaining a certain number of Continuing Medical Education credits, or CME's.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] In 2009, New Mexico and Oregon became the first two states to require licensure of sonographers.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] The American Society of Echocardiography (ASE) is a professional organization made up of physicians, sonographers, nurses, and scientists involved in the field of echocardiography.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] One of the most important roles that the ASE plays is providing their recommendations through the ASE Guidelines and Standards, providing resource and educational opportunities for sonographers and physicians in the field.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/echocardiography] There have been various institutes who are working on use of Artificial intelligence in Echo but they are at a very early stage and still needs full development.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Ultrasound is composed of sound waves with frequencies greater than 20,000 Hz, which is the approximate upper threshold of human hearing.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Ultrasonic images, also known as sonograms, are created by sending pulses of ultrasound into tissue using a probe.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] The ultrasound pulses echo off tissues with different reflection properties and are returned to the probe which records and displays them as an image.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] A general-purpose ultrasonic transducer may be used for most imaging purposes but some situations may require the use of a specialized transducer.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Most ultrasound examination is done using a transducer on the surface of the body, but improved visualization is often possible if a transducer can be placed inside the body.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] For this purpose, special-use transducers, including transvaginal, endorectal, and transesophageal transducers are commonly employed.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] At the extreme, very small transducers can be mounted on small diameter catheters and placed within blood vessels to image the walls and disease of those vessels.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] The imaging mode refers to probe and machine settings that result in specific dimensions of the ultrasound image.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Most machines convert two-way time to imaging depth using as assumed speed of sound of 1540 m/s.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] As the actual speed of sound varies greatly in different tissue types, an ultrasound image is therefore not a true tomographic representation of the body.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Three-dimensional imaging is done by combining B-mode images, using dedicated rotating or stationary probes.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] This has been referred to as **C-mode**.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] A hybrid rotating ultrasound/photoacoustic system produces 3D images, including blood and tissue without the use of magnets or ionizing radiation.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] It uses an arc of detectors to create a volumetric image.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] A laser pulse causes hemoglobin molecules to vibrate and generate acoustic signal also absorbed by the detectors.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] An imaging technique is the method of signal generation and processing that supports in a specific application.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Therapeutic ultrasound aimed at a specific tumor or calculus is not an imaging mode.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] However, for positioning a treatment probe to focus on a specific region of interest, A-mode and B-mode are typically used, often during treatment.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Sonography (ultrasonography) is widely used in medicine.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] It is possible to perform both diagnosis and therapeutic procedures, using ultrasound to guide interventional procedures such as biopsies or to drain collections of fluid, which can be both diagnostic and therapeutic.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Sonographers are medical professionals who perform scans which are traditionally interpreted by radiologists, physicians who specialize in the application and interpretation of medical imaging modalities, or by cardiologists in the case of cardiac ultrasonography (echocardiography).
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Sonography is effective for imaging soft tissues of the body.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Superficial structures such as muscle, tendon, testis, breast, thyroid and parathyroid glands, and the neonatal brain are imaged at higher frequencies (7–18 MHz), which provide better linear (axial) and horizontal (lateral) resolution.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Deeper structures such as liver and kidney are imaged at lower frequencies (1–6 MHz) with lower axial and lateral resolution as a price of deeper tissue penetration.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] In anesthesiology, ultrasound is commonly used to guide the placement of needles when injecting local anesthetic solutions in the proximity of nerves identified within the ultrasound image (nerve block).
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] It is also used for vascular access such as cannulation of large central veins and for difficult arterial cannulation.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Transcranial Doppler is frequently used by neuro-anesthesiologists for obtaining information about flow-velocity in the basal cerebral vessels.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] In angiology or vascular medicine, duplex ultrasound (B Mode imaging combined with Doppler flow measurement) is used to diagnose arterial and venous disease.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] This is particularly important in potential neurologic problems, where carotid ultrasound is commonly used for assessing blood flow and potential or suspected stenosis in the carotid arteries, while transcranial Doppler is used for imaging flow in the intracerebral arteries.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Intravascular ultrasound (*IVUS*) uses a specially designed catheter with a miniaturized ultrasound probe attached to its distal end, which is then threaded inside a blood vessel.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] The proximal end of the catheter is attached to computerized ultrasound equipment and allows the application of ultrasound technology, such as a piezoelectric transducer or capacitive micromachined ultrasonic transducer, to visualize the endothelium of blood vessels in living individuals.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] A 2D color Doppler echocardiogram in the parasternal long-axis (PLAX) view demonstrating a jet of mitral valve regurgitation (valvular insufficiency) into the left atrium.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Echocardiography is an essential tool in cardiology, assisting in evaluation of heart valve function, such as stenosis or insufficiency, strength of cardiac muscle contraction, and hypertrophy or dilatation of the main chambers.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Point of care ultrasound has many applications in emergency medicine.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] These include differentiating cardiac from pulmonary causes of acute breathlessness, and the Focused Assessment with Sonography for Trauma (FAST) exam, extended to include assessment for significant hemoperitoneum or pericardial tamponade after trauma (EFAST).
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Other uses include assisting with differentiating causes of abdominal pain such as gallstones and kidney stones.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Both abdominal and endoanal ultrasound are frequently used in gastroenterology and colorectal surgery.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] In abdominal sonography, the major organs of the abdomen such as the pancreas, aorta, inferior vena cava, liver, gall bladder, bile ducts, kidneys, and spleen may be imaged.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] However, sound waves may be blocked by gas in the bowel and attenuated to differing degrees by fat, sometimes limiting diagnostic capabilities.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] The appendix can sometimes be seen when inflamed (e.g.: appendicitis) and ultrasound is the initial imaging choice, avoiding radiation if possible, although it frequently needs to be followed by other imaging methods such as CT.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Endoanal ultrasound is used particularly in the investigation of anorectal symptoms such as fecal incontinence or obstructed defecation.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] It images the immediate perianal anatomy and is able to detect occult defects such as tearing of the anal sphincter.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Ultrasonography of liver tumors allows for both detection and characterization.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Ultrasound imaging studies are often obtained during the evaluation process of Fatty liver disease.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Ultrasonography reveals a "bright" liver with increased echogenicity.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Pocket-sized ultrasound devices might be used as point-of-care screening tools to diagnose liver steatosis.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Gynecologic ultrasonography examines female pelvic organs (specifically the uterus, ovaries, and fallopian tubes) as well as the bladder, adnexa, and pouch of Douglas.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] It uses transducers designed for approaches through the lower abdominal wall, curvilinear and sector, and specialty transducers such as transvaginal ultrasound.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Obstetrical sonography was originally developed in the late 1950s and 1960s by Ian Donald and is commonly used during pregnancy to check the development and presentation of the fetus.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] It can be used to identify many conditions that could be potentially harmful to the mother and/or baby possibly remaining undiagnosed or with delayed diagnosis in the absence of sonography.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] It is currently believed that the risk of delayed diagnosis is greater than the small risk, if any, associated with undergoing an ultrasound scan.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] However, its use for non-medical purposes such as fetal "keepsake" videos and photos is discouraged.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Nonetheless, care should be taken to use low power settings and avoid pulsed wave scanning of the fetal brain unless specifically indicated in high risk pregnancies.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Figures released for the period 2005–2006 by the UK Government (Department of Health) show that non-obstetric ultrasound examinations constituted more than 65% of the total number of ultrasound scans conducted.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Blood velocity can be measured in various blood vessels, such as middle cerebral artery or descending aorta, by relatively inexpensive and low risk ultrasound Doppler probes attached to portable monitors.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] These provide non-invasive or transcutaneous (non-piercing) minimal invasive blood flow assessment.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Common examples are transcranial Doppler, esophageal Doppler and suprasternal Doppler.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Most structures of the neck, including the thyroid and parathyroid glands, lymph nodes, and salivary glands, are well-visualized by high-frequency ultrasound with exceptional anatomic detail.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Ultrasound is the preferred imaging modality for thyroid tumors and lesions, and its use is important in the evaluation, preoperative planning, and postoperative surveillance of patients with thyroid cancer.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Many other benign and malignant conditions in the head and neck can be differentiated, evaluated, and managed with the help of diagnostic ultrasound and ultrasound-guided procedures.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] In neonatology, transcranial Doppler can be used for basic assessment of intracerebral structural abnormalities, suspected hemorrhage, ventriculomegaly or hydrocephalus and anoxic insults (periventricular leukomalacia).
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] It can be performed through the soft spots in the skull of a newborn infant (fontanelle) until these completely close at about 1 year of age by which time they have formed a virtually impenetrable acoustic barrier to ultrasound.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] The most common site for cranial ultrasound is the anterior fontanelle.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] The smaller the fontanelle, the more the image is compromised.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Lung ultrasound has been found to be useful in diagnosing common neonatal respiratory diseases such as transient tachypnea of the newborn, respiratory distress syndrome, congenital pneumonia, meconium aspiration syndrome, and pneumothorax.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] A neonatal lung ultrasound score, first described by Brat et al., has been found to highly correlate with oxygenation in the newborn.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Ultrasound is used to assess the lungs in a variety of settings including critical care, emergency medicine, trauma surgery, as well as general medicine and nursing.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Although air present in the lungs does not allow good penetration of ultrasound waves, interpretation of specific artifacts created on the lung surface can be used to detect abnormalities.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Lung, or pulmonary ultrasound does not visualise the lung itself, but the tissue-air-interface at the pleural line.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] The fact that artefact interpretation is essential sets lung ultrasound apart from modalities aimed at imaging an actual organ.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] This distinction has mechanical implications that are important when trying to interpret artifactual patterns.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Where modern sonography is aided by software filters and acoustic harmonics to enhance visualisation of organs such as the heart or liver, they corrupt the specific patterns sought in lung ultrasound.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Therefore, a software preset void of imaging filters, harmonic imaging, and beam compounding, is preferred.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Ultrasound is routinely used in urology to determine the amount of fluid retained in a patient's bladder.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] In a pelvic sonogram, images include the uterus and ovaries or urinary bladder in females.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] In males, a sonogram will provide information about the bladder, prostate, or testicles (for example to urgently distinguish epididymitis from testicular torsion).
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] In young males, it is used to distinguish more benign testicular masses (varicocele or hydrocele) from testicular cancer, which is curable but must be treated to preserve health and fertility.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] There are two methods of performing pelvic sonography – externally or internally.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] The internal pelvic sonogram is performed either transvaginally (in a woman) or transrectally (in a man).
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] It is also used to diagnose and, at higher frequencies, to treat (break up) kidney stones or kidney crystals (nephrolithiasis).
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Scrotal ultrasonography is used in the evaluation of testicular pain, and can help identify solid masses.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Ultrasound is an excellent method for the study of the penis, such as indicated in trauma, priapism, erectile dysfunction or suspected Peyronie's disease.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Musculoskeletal ultrasound is used to examine tendons, muscles, nerves, ligaments, soft tissue masses, and bone surfaces.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] It is helpful in diagnosing ligament sprains, muscles strains and joint pathology.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] It is an alternative or supplement to x-ray imaging in detecting fractures of the wrist, elbow and shoulder for patients up to 12 years (Fracture sonography).
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Ultrasound can also be used for needle guidance in muscle or joint injections, as in ultrasound-guided hip joint injection.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] In nephrology, ultrasonography of the kidneys is essential in the diagnosis and management of kidney-related diseases.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] The kidneys are easily examined, and most pathological changes are distinguishable with ultrasound.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] It is an accessible, versatile, relatively economic, and fast aid for decision-making in patients with renal symptoms and for guidance in renal intervention.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Using B-mode imaging, assessment of renal anatomy is easily performed, and US is often used as image guidance for renal interventions.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Furthermore, novel applications in renal US have been introduced with contrast-enhanced ultrasound (CEUS), elastography and fusion imaging.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] However, renal US has certain limitations, and other modalities, such as CT (CECT) and MRI, should be considered for supplementary imaging in assessing renal disease.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Intravenous access, for the collection of blood samples to assist in diagnosis or laboratory investigation including blood culture, or for administration of intravenous fluids for fluid maintenance of replacement or blood transfusion in sicker patients, is a common medical procedure.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] The need for intravenous access occurs in the outpatient laboratory, in the inpatient hospital units, and most critically in the Emergency Room and Intensive Care Unit.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] In many situations, intravenous access may be required repeatedly or over a significant time period.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] In these latter circumstances, a needle with an overlying catheter is introduced into the vein and the catheter is then inserted securely into the vein while the needle is withdrawn.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] The chosen veins are most frequently selected from the arm, but in challenging situations, a deeper vein from the neck (external jugular vein) or upper arm (subclavian vein) may need to be used.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] There are many reasons why the selection of a suitable vein may be problematic.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] These include, but are not limited to, obesity, previous injury to veins from inflammatory reaction to previous 'blood draws', previous injury to veins from recreational drug use.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] In these challenging situations, the insertion of a catheter into a vein has been greatly assisted by the use of ultrasound.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] The ultrasound unit may be 'cart-based' or 'handheld' using a linear transducer with a frequency of 10 to 15 megahertz.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] In most circumstances, choice of vein will be limited by the requirement that the vein is within 1.5 cms. from the skin surface.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] The transducer may be placed longitudinally or transversely over the chosen vein.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Ultrasound training for intravenous cannulation is offered in most ultrasound training programs.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] The creation of an image from sound has three steps – transmitting a sound wave, receiving echoes, and interpreting those echoes.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] A sound wave is typically produced by a piezoelectric transducer encased in a plastic housing.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Strong, short electrical pulses from the ultrasound machine drive the transducer at the desired frequency.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] The frequencies can vary between 1 and 18 MHz, though frequencies up to 50–100 megahertz have been used experimentally in a technique known as biomicroscopy in special regions, such as the anterior chamber of the eye.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Older technology transducers focused their beam with physical lenses.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Contemporary technology transducers use digital antenna array techniques (piezoelectric elements in the transducer produce echoes at different times) to enable the ultrasound machine to change the direction and depth of focus.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Therefore, the wider the transducer width and the higher the frequency of ultrasound, the longer the Fresnel zone, and the lateral resolution can be maintained at a greater depth from the transducer.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Therefore, a shorter pulse length requires higher bandwidth (greater number of frequencies) to constitute the ultrasound pulse.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] As stated, the sound is focused either by the shape of the transducer, a lens in front of the transducer, or a complex set of control pulses from the ultrasound scanner, in the beamforming or spatial filtering technique.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] This focusing produces an arc-shaped sound wave from the face of the transducer.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] The wave travels into the body and comes into focus at a desired depth.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Materials on the face of the transducer enable the sound to be transmitted efficiently into the body (often a rubbery coating, a form of impedance matching).
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] In addition, a water-based gel is placed between the patient's skin and the probe to facilitate ultrasound transmission into the body.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] This is because air causes total reflection of ultrasound; impeding the transmission of ultrasound into the body.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] The sound wave is partially reflected from the layers between different tissues or scattered from smaller structures.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Specifically, sound is reflected anywhere where there are acoustic impedance changes in the body: e.g. blood cells in blood plasma, small structures in organs, etc.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Some of the reflections return to the transducer.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] The return of the sound wave to the transducer results in the same process as sending the sound wave, in reverse.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] The returned sound wave vibrates the transducer and the transducer turns the vibrations into electrical pulses that travel to the ultrasonic scanner where they are processed and transformed into a digital image.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Once the ultrasonic scanner determines these two, it can locate which pixel in the image to illuminate and with what intensity.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Transforming the received signal into a digital image may be explained by using a blank spreadsheet as an analogy.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] First picture a long, flat transducer at the top of the sheet.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Send pulses down the 'columns' of the spreadsheet (A, B, C, etc.).
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Listen at each column for any return echoes.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] When an echo is heard, note how long it took for the echo to return.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] The longer the wait, the deeper the row (1,2,3, etc.).
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] The strength of the echo determines the brightness setting for that cell (white for a strong echo, black for a weak echo, and varying shades of grey for everything in between.) When all the echoes are recorded on the sheet, a greyscale image has been accomplished.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] In modern ultrasound systems, images are derived from the combined reception of echoes by multiple elements, rather than a single one.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] These elements in the transducer array work together to receive signals, a process essential for optimizing the ultrasonic beam's focus and producing detailed images.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] One predominant method for this is "delay-and-sum" beamforming.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] The time delay applied to each element is calculated based on the geometrical relationship between the imaging point, the transducer, and receiver positions.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] By integrating these time-adjusted signals, the system pinpoints focus onto specific tissue regions, enhancing image resolution and clarity.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] The utilization of multiple element reception combined with the delay-and-sum principles underpins the high-quality images characteristic of contemporary ultrasound scans.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Images from the ultrasound scanner are transferred and displayed using the DICOM standard.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Normally, very little post processing is applied.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Ultrasonography (sonography) uses a probe containing multiple acoustic transducers to send pulses of sound into a material.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Whenever a sound wave encounters a material with a different density (acoustical impedance), some of the sound wave is scattered but part is reflected back to the probe and is detected as an echo.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] The time it takes for the echo to travel back to the probe is measured and used to calculate the depth of the tissue interface causing the echo.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] The greater the difference between acoustic impedances, the larger the echo is.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] If the pulse hits gases or solids, the density difference is so great that most of the acoustic energy is reflected and it becomes impossible to progress further.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] The frequencies used for medical imaging are generally in the range of 1 to 18 MHz.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Higher frequencies have a correspondingly smaller wavelength, and can be used to make more detailed sonograms.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] However, the attenuation of the sound wave is increased at higher frequencies, so penetration of deeper tissues necessitates a lower frequency (3–5 MHz).
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Penetrating deep into the body with sonography is difficult.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Some acoustic energy is lost each time an echo is formed, but most of it (approximately $\textstyle 0.5{\frac {\mbox{dB}}{{\mbox{cm depth}}\cdot {\mbox{MHz}}}}$ ) is lost from acoustic absorption.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] The speed of sound varies as it travels through different materials, and is dependent on the acoustical impedance of the material.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] However, the sonographic instrument assumes that the acoustic velocity is constant at 1540 m/s.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] An effect of this assumption is that in a real body with non-uniform tissues, the beam becomes somewhat de-focused and image resolution is reduced.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] To generate a 2-D image, the ultrasonic beam is swept.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] A transducer may be swept mechanically by rotating or swinging or a 1-D phased array transducer may be used to sweep the beam electronically.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] The received data is processed and used to construct the image.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] The image is then a 2-D representation of the slice into the body.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] 3-D images can be generated by acquiring a series of adjacent 2-D images.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Commonly a specialized probe that mechanically scans a conventional 2-D image transducer is used.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] However, since the mechanical scanning is slow, it is difficult to make 3D images of moving tissues.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Recently, 2-D phased array transducers that can sweep the beam in 3-D have been developed.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] These can image faster and can even be used to make live 3-D images of a beating heart.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Doppler ultrasonography is used to study blood flow and muscle motion.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] The different detected speeds are represented in color for ease of interpretation, for example leaky heart valves: the leak shows up as a flash of unique color.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p01] Colors may alternatively be used to represent the amplitudes of the received echoes.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] An additional expansion of ultrasound is **bi-planar ultrasound**, in which the probe has two 2D planes perpendicular to each other, providing more efficient localization and detection.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] Furthermore, an **omniplane** probe can rotate 180° to obtain multiple images.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] In 3D ultrasound, many 2D planes are digitally added together to create a 3-dimensional image of the object.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] Doppler ultrasonography employs the Doppler effect to assess whether structures (usually blood) are moving towards or away from the probe, and their relative velocity.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] By calculating the frequency shift of a particular sample volume, flow in an artery or a jet of blood flow over a heart valve, its speed and direction can be determined and visualized, as an example.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] *Color Doppler* is the measurement of velocity by color scale.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] Color Doppler images are generally combined with gray scale (B-mode) images to display *duplex ultrasonography* images.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] A contrast medium for medical ultrasonography is a formulation of encapsulated gaseous microbubbles to increase echogenicity of blood, discovered by Dr.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] Raymond Gramiak in 1968 and named contrast-enhanced ultrasound.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] This contrast medical imaging modality is used throughout the world, for echocardiography in particular in the United States and for ultrasound radiology in Europe and Asia.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] Microbubbles-based contrast media is administered intravenously into the patient blood stream during the ultrasonography examination.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] Due to their size, the microbubbles remain confined in blood vessels without extravasating towards the interstitial fluid.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] An ultrasound contrast media is therefore purely intravascular, making it an ideal agent to image organ microvasculature for diagnostic purposes.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] A typical clinical use of contrast ultrasonography is detection of a hypervascular metastatic tumor, which exhibits a contrast uptake (kinetics of microbubbles concentration in blood circulation) faster than healthy biological tissue surrounding the tumor.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] Other clinical applications using contrast exist, as in echocardiography to improve delineation of left ventricle for visualizing contractibility of heart muscle after a myocardial infarction.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] Finally, applications in quantitative perfusion (relative measurement of blood flow) have emerged for identifying early patient response to anti-cancerous drug treatment (methodology and clinical study by Dr.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] Nathalie Lassau in 2011), enabling the best oncological therapeutic options to be determined.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] In oncological practice of medical contrast ultrasonography, clinicians use 'parametric imaging of vascular signatures' invented by Dr.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] This method is conceived as a cancer aided diagnostic tool, facilitating characterization of a suspicious tumor (malignant versus benign) in an organ.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] This method is based on medical computational science to analyze a time sequence of ultrasound contrast images, a digital video recorded in real-time during patient examination.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] Once signal processing in each pixel is completed, a color spatial map of the parameter is displayed on a computer monitor, summarizing all vascular information of the tumor in a single image called a parametric image (see last figure of press article as clinical examples).
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] This parametric image is interpreted by clinicians based on predominant colorization of the tumor: red indicates a suspicion of malignancy (risk of cancer), green or yellow – a high probability of benignity.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] In the first case (suspicion of malignant tumor), the clinician typically prescribes a biopsy to confirm the diagnostic or a CT scan examination as a second opinion.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] In the second case (quasi-certain of benign tumor), only a follow-up is needed with a contrast ultrasonography examination a few months later.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] The main clinical benefits are to avoid a systemic biopsy (with inherent risks of invasive procedures) of benign tumors or a CT scan examination exposing the patient to X-ray radiation.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] The parametric imaging of vascular signatures method proved to be effective in humans for characterization of tumors in the liver.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] In a cancer screening context, this method might be potentially applicable to other organs such as breast or prostate.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] The current future of contrast ultrasonography is in molecular imaging with potential clinical applications expected in cancer screening to detect malignant tumors at their earliest stage of appearance.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] As a result, a few minutes after their injection in blood circulation, the targeted microbubbles accumulate in the malignant tumor; facilitating its localization in a unique ultrasound contrast image.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] In 2013, the very first exploratory clinical trial in humans for prostate cancer was completed at Amsterdam in the Netherlands by Dr.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] In molecular ultrasonography, the technique of acoustic radiation force (also used for shear wave elastography) is applied in order to literally push the targeted microbubbles towards microvessels wall; first demonstrated by Dr.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] This allows maximization of binding to the malignant tumor; the targeted microbubbles being in more direct contact with cancerous biomolecules expressed at the inner surface of tumoral microvessels.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] At the stage of scientific preclinical research, the technique of acoustic radiation force was implemented as a prototype in clinical ultrasound systems and validated *in vivo* in 2D and 3D imaging modes.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] Ultrasound is also used for elastography, which is a relatively new imaging modality that maps the elastic properties of soft tissue.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] This modality emerged in the last two decades.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] Elastography is useful in medical diagnoses as it can discern healthy from unhealthy tissue for specific organs/growths.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] For example, cancerous tumors will often be harder than the surrounding tissue, and diseased livers are stiffer than healthy ones.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] There are many ultrasound elastography techniques.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] Interventional ultrasonography involves biopsy, emptying fluids, intrauterine Blood transfusion (Hemolytic disease of the newborn).
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] Compression ultrasonography is when the probe is pressed against the skin.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] This can bring the target structure closer to the probe, increasing spatial resolution of it.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] Comparison of the shape of the target structure before and after compression can aid in diagnosis.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] It is used in ultrasonography of deep venous thrombosis, wherein absence of vein compressibility is a strong indicator of thrombosis.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] Compression ultrasonography has both high sensitivity and specificity for detecting proximal deep vein thrombosis in symptomatic patients.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] Results are not reliable when the patient is asymptomatic, for example in high risk postoperative orthopedic patients.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] Panoramic ultrasonography is the digital stitching of multiple ultrasound images into a broader one.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] It can display an entire abnormality and show its relationship to nearby structures on a single image.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] Multiparametric ultrasonography (mpUSS) combines multiple ultrasound techniques to produce a composite result.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] For example, one study combined B-mode, colour Doppler, real-time elastography, and contrast-enhanced ultrasound, achieving an accuracy similar to that of multiparametric MRI.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] Speed-of-sound (SoS) imaging aims to find the spatial distribution of the SoS within the tissue.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] The idea is to find relative delay measurements for different transmission events and solve the limited-angle tomographic reconstruction problem using delay measurements and transmission geometry.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] Compared to shear-wave elastography, SoS imaging has better ex-vivo tissue differentiation for benign and malignant tumors.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] As with all imaging modalities, ultrasonography has positive and negative attributes.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] Following research into patient cooperation, research into public perceptions of ultrasound has used social media listening to surface patient experiences not typically captured in clinical records.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] A 2025 study presented at the SPIE Medical Imaging conference analysed posts across Twitter, Threads, Facebook, and social forums using Pulsar platform alongside topic modelling and retrieval-augmented generation.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] "Diagnostic ultrasound is recognized as a safe, effective, and highly flexible imaging modality capable of providing clinically relevant information about most parts of the body in a rapid and cost-effective fashion".
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] Diagnostic ultrasound studies of the fetus are generally considered to be safe during pregnancy.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] However, this diagnostic procedure should be performed only when there is a valid medical indication, and the lowest possible ultrasonic exposure setting should be used to gain the necessary diagnostic information under the "as low as reasonably practicable" or ALARP principle.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] Although there is no evidence that ultrasound could be harmful to the fetus, medical authorities typically strongly discourage the promotion, selling, or leasing of ultrasound equipment for making "keepsake fetal videos".
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] Diagnostic and therapeutic ultrasound equipment is regulated in the US by the Food and Drug Administration, and worldwide by other national regulatory agencies.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] The FDA limits acoustic output using several metrics; generally, other agencies accept the FDA-established guidelines.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] Currently, New Mexico, Oregon, and North Dakota are the only US states that regulate diagnostic medical sonographers.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] Certification examinations for sonographers are available in the US from three organizations: the American Registry for Diagnostic Medical Sonography, Cardiovascular Credentialing International and the American Registry of Radiologic Technologists.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] The primary regulated metrics are Mechanical Index (MI), a metric associated with the cavitation bio-effect, and Thermal Index (TI) a metric associated with the tissue heating bio-effect.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] The FDA requires that the machine not exceed established limits, which are reasonably conservative in an effort to maintain diagnostic ultrasound as a safe imaging modality.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] This requires self-regulation on the part of the manufacturer in terms of machine calibration.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] Ultrasound-based pre-natal care and sex screening technologies were launched in India in the 1980s.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] With concerns about its misuse for sex-selective abortion, the Government of India passed the Pre-natal Diagnostic Techniques Act (PNDT) in 1994 to distinguish and regulate legal and illegal uses of ultrasound equipment.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] The law was further amended as the Pre-Conception and Pre-natal Diagnostic Techniques (Regulation and Prevention of Misuse) (PCPNDT) Act in 2004 to deter and punish prenatal sex screening and sex selective abortion.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] It is currently illegal and a punishable crime in India to determine or disclose the sex of a fetus using ultrasound equipment.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] Ultrasound is also a valuable tool in veterinary medicine, offering the same non-invasive imaging that helps in the diagnosis and monitoring of conditions in animals.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] After the French physicist Pierre Curie's discovery of piezoelectricity in 1880, ultrasonic waves could be deliberately generated for industry.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] In 1940, the American acoustical physicist Floyd Firestone devised the first ultrasonic echo imaging device, the Supersonic Reflectoscope, to detect internal flaws in metal castings.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] In 1941, Austrian neurologist Karl Theo Dussik, in collaboration with his brother, Friedrich, a physicist, was likely the first person to image the human body ultrasonically, outlining the ventricles of a human brain.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] Ultrasonic energy was first applied to the human body for medical purposes by Dr George Ludwig at the Naval Medical Research Institute, Bethesda, Maryland, in the late 1940s.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] English-born physicist John Wild (1914–2009) first used ultrasound to assess the thickness of bowel tissue as early as 1949; he has been described as the "father of medical ultrasound".
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] Subsequent advances took place concurrently in several countries but it was not until 1961 that David Robinson and George Kossoff's work at the Australian Department of Health resulted in the first commercially practical water bath ultrasonic scanner.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] In 1963 Meyerdirk & Wright launched production of the first commercial, hand-held, articulated arm, compound contact B-mode scanner, which made ultrasound generally available for medical use.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] Parallel developments in Glasgow, Scotland by Professor Ian Donald and colleagues at the Glasgow Royal Maternity Hospital (GRMH) led to the first diagnostic applications of the technique.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] Donald was an obstetrician with a self-confessed "childish interest in machines, electronic and otherwise", who, having treated the wife of one of the company's directors, was invited to visit the Research Department of boilermakers Babcock & Wilcox at Renfrew.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] He adapted their industrial ultrasound equipment to conduct experiments on various anatomical specimens and assess their ultrasonic characteristics.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] Together with the medical physicist Tom Brown. and fellow obstetrician John MacVicar, Donald refined the equipment to enable differentiation of pathology in live volunteer patients.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] These findings were reported in *The Lancet* on 7 June 1958 as "Investigation of Abdominal Masses by Pulsed Ultrasound" – possibly one of the most important papers published in the field of diagnostic medical imaging.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] At GRMH, Professor Donald and James Willocks then refined their techniques to obstetric applications including fetal head measurement to assess the size and growth of the fetus.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] With the opening of the new Queen Mother's Hospital in Yorkhill in 1964, it became possible to improve these methods even further.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] Stuart Campbell's pioneering work on fetal cephalometry led to it acquiring long-term status as the definitive method of study of foetal growth.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] As the technical quality of the scans was further developed, it soon became possible to study pregnancy from start to finish and diagnose its many complications such as multiple pregnancy, fetal abnormality and *placenta praevia*.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] Diagnostic ultrasound has since been imported into practically every other area of medicine.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] Medical ultrasonography was used in 1953 at Lund University by cardiologist Inge Edler and Gustav Ludwig Hertz's son Carl Hellmuth Hertz, who was then a graduate student at the university's department of nuclear physics.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] Edler had asked Hertz if it was possible to use radar to look into the body, but Hertz said this was impossible.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] However, he said, it might be possible to use ultrasonography.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] Hertz was familiar with using ultrasonic reflectoscopes of the American acoustical physicist Floyd Firestone's invention for nondestructive materials testing, and together Edler and Hertz developed the idea of applying this methodology in medicine.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] The first successful measurement of heart activity was made on October 29, 1953, using a device borrowed from the ship construction company Kockums in Malmö.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] On December 16 the same year, the method was applied to generate an echo-encephalogram (ultrasonic probe of the brain).
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] Edler and Hertz published their findings in 1954.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] In 1962, after about two years of work, Joseph Holmes, William Wright, and Ralph Meyerdirk developed the first compound contact B-mode scanner.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] Public Health Services and the University of Colorado.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] Wright and Meyerdirk left the university to form Physionic Engineering Inc., which launched the first commercial hand-held articulated arm compound contact B-mode scanner in 1963.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] This was the start of the most popular design in the history of ultrasound scanners.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] In the late 1960s Gene Strandness and the bio-engineering group at the University of Washington conducted research on Doppler ultrasound as a diagnostic tool for vascular disease.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] Eventually, they developed technologies to use duplex imaging, or Doppler in conjunction with B-mode scanning, to view vascular structures in real time while also providing hemodynamic information.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/medical-ultrasound-p02] The first demonstration of color Doppler was by Geoff Stevenson, who was involved in the early developments and medical use of Doppler shifted ultrasonic energy.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/transducer] A **transducer** is a device that usefully converts energy from one form to another.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/transducer] Usually a transducer converts a signal in one form of energy to a signal in another.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/transducer] Transducers are often employed at the boundaries of automation, measurement, and control systems, where electrical signals are converted to and from other physical quantities (energy, force, torque, light, motion, position, etc.).
[src:ultrasound-imaging/transducer] The process of converting one form of energy to another is known as transduction.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/transducer] Passive transducers require an external power source to operate, which is called an excitation signal.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/transducer] The signal is modulated by the sensor to produce an output signal.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/transducer] For example, a thermistor does not generate any electrical signal, but by passing an electric current through it, its resistance can be measured by detecting variations in the current or voltage across the thermistor.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/transducer] Active transducers in contrast, generate electric current in response to an external stimulus which serves as the output signal without the need of an additional energy source.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/transducer] Such examples are a photodiode, and a piezoelectric sensor, photovoltaic, thermocouple.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] Ultrasound can be used for measuring wind speed and direction (anemometer), tank or channel fluid level, and speed through air or water.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] For measuring speed or direction, a device uses multiple detectors and calculates the speed from the relative distances to particulates in the air or water.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] To measure tank or channel liquid level, and also sea level (tide gauge), the sensor measures the distance (ranging) to the surface of the fluid.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] Further applications include: humidifiers, sonar, medical ultrasonography, burglar alarms and non-destructive testing.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] Systems typically use a transducer that generates sound waves in the ultrasonic range, above 20 kHz, by turning electrical energy into sound, then upon receiving the echo turn the sound waves into electrical energy which can be measured and displayed.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] This technology, as well, can detect approaching objects and track their positions.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] Ultrasound can also be used to make point-to-point distance measurements by transmitting and receiving discrete bursts of ultrasound between transducers.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] This technique is known as sonomicrometry, where the transit-time of the ultrasound signal is measured electronically (ie digitally) and converted mathematically to the distance between transducers assuming the speed of sound of the medium between the transducers is known.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] This method can be very precise in terms of temporal and spatial resolution because the time-of-flight measurement can be derived from tracking the same incident (received) waveform either by reference level or zero crossing.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] This enables the measurement resolution to far exceed the wavelength of the sound frequency generated by the transducers.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] Ultrasonic transducers convert alternating current (AC) into ultrasound and vice versa.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] The transducers typically use piezoelectric transducers or capacitive transducers to generate or receive ultrasound.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] Piezoelectric crystals are able to change their sizes and shapes in response to voltage being applied.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] On the other hand, capacitive transducers use electrostatic fields between a conductive diaphragm and a backing plate.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] The beam pattern of a transducer can be determined by the active transducer area and shape, the ultrasound wavelength, and the sound velocity of the propagation medium.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] The diagrams show the sound fields of an unfocused and a focusing ultrasonic transducer in water, plainly at differing energy levels.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] Since piezoelectric materials generate a voltage when force is applied to them, they can also work as ultrasonic detectors.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] Some systems use separate transmitters and receivers, while others combine both functions into a single piezoelectric transceiver.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] Ultrasound transmitters can also use non-piezoelectric principles such as magnetostriction.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] Materials with this property change size slightly when exposed to a magnetic field and make practical transducers.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] A capacitor ("condenser") microphone has a thin diaphragm that responds to ultrasound waves.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] Changes in the electric field between the diaphragm and a closely spaced backing plate convert sound signals to electric currents, which can be amplified.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] The diaphragm (or membrane) principle is also used in the relatively new micro-machined ultrasonic transducers (MUTs).
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] These devices are fabricated using silicon micro-machining technology (MEMS technology), which is particularly useful for the fabrication of transducer arrays.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] The vibration of the diaphragm may be measured or induced electronically using the capacitance between the diaphragm and a closely spaced backing plate (CMUT), or by adding a thin layer of piezo-electric material on the diaphragm (PMUT).
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] Alternatively, recent research showed that the vibration of the diaphragm may be measured by a tiny optical ring resonator integrated inside the diaphragm (OMUS).
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] Ultrasonic transducers can also be used for acoustic levitation.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] It involves transmitting acoustic waves into water and recording the time interval between emission and return of a pulse; the resulting time of flight, along with knowledge of the speed of sound in water, allows determining the distance between sonar and target.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] This information is then typically used for navigation purposes or in order to obtain depths for charting purposes.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] Echo sounding is effectively a special purpose application of sonar used to locate the bottom.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] Since a traditional pre-SI unit of water depth was the fathom, an instrument used for determining water depth is sometimes called a *fathometer*.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] The first practical fathometer was invented by Herbert Grove Dorsey and patented in 1928.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] Medical ultrasonic transducers (probes) come in a variety of different shapes and sizes for use in making cross-sectional images of various parts of the body.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] The transducer may be used in contact with the skin, as in fetal ultrasound imaging, or inserted into a body opening such as the rectum or vagina.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] Clinicians who perform ultrasound-guided procedures often use a probe positioning system to hold the ultrasonic transducer.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] Compared to other medical imaging modalities, ultrasound has several advantages.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] It provides images in real-time, is portable, and can consequently be brought to the bedside.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] It is substantially lower in cost than other imaging strategies and does not use harmful ionizing radiation.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] Drawbacks include various limits on its field of view, the need for patient cooperation, dependence on patient physique, difficulty imaging structures obscured by bone, air or gases, and the necessity of a skilled operator, usually with professional training.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] Owing to these drawbacks, novel wearable ultrasound implementations are gaining popularity.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] These miniature devices continuously monitor vitals and alert at the emergence of early signs of abnormality.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] Ultrasonic sensors can detect the movement of targets and measure the distance to them in many automated factories and process plants.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] Sensors can have an on or off digital output for detecting the movement of objects, or an analog output proportional to distance.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] They can sense the edge of the material as part of a web guiding system.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] Ultrasonic sensors are widely used in cars as parking sensors to aid the driver in reversing into parking spaces.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] They are being tested for a number of other automotive uses including ultrasonic people detection and assisting in autonomous UAV navigation.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] Because ultrasonic sensors use sound rather than light for detection, they work in applications where photoelectric sensors may not.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] Ultrasonics is a great solution for clear object detection and for liquid level measurement, applications that photoelectrics struggle with because of target translucence.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] As well, target color or reflectivity do not affect ultrasonic sensors, which can operate reliably in high-glare environments.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] Passive ultrasonic sensors may be used to detect high-pressure gas or liquid leaks, or other hazardous conditions that generate ultrasonic sound.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] In these devices, ultrasound from the transducer (microphone) is converted down to the human hearing range (Audible Sound = 20 Hz to 20 kHz).
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] High-power ultrasonic emitters are used in commercially available ultrasonic cleaning devices.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] An ultrasonic transducer is affixed to a stainless steel pan which is filled with a solvent (frequently water or isopropanol).
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] An electrical square wave feeds the transducer, creating sound in the solvent strong enough to cause cavitation.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] Ultrasonic technology has been used for multiple cleaning purposes.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] One of which that been gaining a decent amount of traction in the past decade is ultrasonic gun cleaning.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] In ultrasonic welding and ultrasonic wire bonding, plastics and metals are joining using vibrations created by power ultrasonic transducers.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound-transducer] Ultrasonic testing is also widely used in metallurgy and engineering to evaluate corrosion, welds, and material defects using different types of scans.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Ultrasound is used in many different fields.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Ultrasonic devices are used to detect objects and measure distances.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Ultrasound imaging or sonography is often used in medicine.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] In the nondestructive testing of products and structures, ultrasound is used to detect invisible flaws.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Industrially, ultrasound is used for cleaning, mixing, and accelerating chemical processes.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Animals such as bats and porpoises use ultrasound for locating prey and obstacles.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Acoustics, the science of sound, starts as far back as Pythagoras in the 6th century BC, who wrote on the mathematical properties of stringed instruments.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Echolocation in bats was discovered by Lazzaro Spallanzani in 1794, when he demonstrated that bats hunted and navigated by inaudible sound, not vision.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Francis Galton in 1893 invented the Galton whistle, an adjustable whistle that produced ultrasound, which he used to measure the hearing range of humans and other animals, demonstrating that many animals could hear sounds above the hearing range of humans.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] The first article on the history of ultrasound was written in 1948.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] According to its author, during the First World War, a Russian engineer named Chilowski submitted an idea for submarine detection to the French Government.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] The latter invited Paul Langevin, then Director of the School of Physics and Chemistry in Paris, to evaluate it.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Chilowski's proposal was to excite a cylindrical, mica condenser by a high-frequency Poulsen arc at approximately 100 kHz and thus to generate an ultrasound beam for detecting submerged objects.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] The idea of locating underwater obstacles had been suggested prior by L.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Richardson, following the *Titanic* disaster.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Richardson had proposed to position a high-frequency hydraulic whistle at the focus of a mirror and use the beam for locating submerged navigational hazards.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] A prototype was built by Sir Charles Parsons, the inventor of the vapour turbine, but the device was found not to be suitable for this purpose.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Langevin's device made use of the piezoelectric effect, which he had been acquainted with whilst a student at the laboratory of Jacques and Pierre Curie.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Langevin calculated and built an ultrasound transducer comprising a thin sheet of quartz sandwiched between two steel plates.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Langevin was the first to report cavitation-related bioeffects from ultrasound.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Ultrasound is defined by the American National Standards Institute as "sound at frequencies greater than 20 kHz".
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] In air at atmospheric pressure, ultrasonic waves have wavelengths of 1.9 cm or less.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Ultrasound can be generated at very high frequencies; ultrasound is used for sonochemistry at frequencies up to multiple hundreds of kilohertz.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Medical imaging equipment uses frequencies in the MHz range.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] UHF ultrasound waves have been generated as high as the gigahertz range.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Characterizing extremely high-frequency ultrasound poses challenges, as such rapid movement causes waveforms to steepen and form shock waves.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] The upper frequency limit in humans (approximately 20 kHz) is due to limitations of the middle ear.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Auditory sensation can occur if high‐intensity ultrasound is fed directly into the human skull and reaches the cochlea through bone conduction, without passing through the middle ear.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Children can hear some high-pitched sounds that older adults cannot hear, because in humans the upper limit pitch of hearing tends to decrease with age.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] An American cell phone company has used this to create ring signals that supposedly are only audible to younger humans, but many older people can hear the signals, which may be because of the considerable variation of age-related deterioration in the upper hearing threshold.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Bats use a variety of ultrasonic ranging (echolocation) techniques to detect their prey.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] They can detect frequencies beyond 100 kHz, possibly up to 200 kHz.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Many insects have good ultrasonic hearing, and most of these are nocturnal insects listening for echolocating bats.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] These include many groups of moths, beetles, praying mantises and lacewings.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Upon hearing a bat, some insects will make evasive manoeuvres to escape being caught.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Ultrasonic frequencies trigger a reflex action in the noctuid moth that causes it to drop slightly in its flight to evade attack.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Tiger moths also emit clicks which may disturb bats' echolocation, and in other cases may advertise the fact that they are poisonous by emitting sound.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Dogs and cats' hearing range extends into the ultrasound; the top end of a dog's hearing range is about 45 kHz, while a cat's is 64 kHz.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] The wild ancestors of cats and dogs evolved this higher hearing range to hear high-frequency sounds made by their preferred prey, small rodents.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] A dog whistle is a whistle that emits ultrasound, used for training and calling dogs.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] The frequency of most dog whistles is within the range of 23 to 54 kHz.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Toothed whales, including dolphins, can hear ultrasound and use such sounds in their navigational system (biosonar) to orient and to capture prey.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Porpoises have the highest known upper hearing limit at around 160 kHz.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Several types of fish can detect ultrasound.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] In the order Clupeiformes, members of the subfamily Alosinae (shad) have been shown to be able to detect sounds up to 180 kHz, while the other subfamilies (e.g. herrings) can hear only up to 4 kHz.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] No bird species have been reported to be sensitive to ultrasound.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Commercial ultrasonic systems have been sold for supposed indoors electronic pest control and outdoors ultrasonic algae control.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] However, no scientific evidence exists on the success of such devices for these purposes.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] An ultrasonic level or sensing system requires no contact with the target.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] For many processes in the medical, pharmaceutical, military and general industries this is an advantage over inline sensors that may contaminate the liquids inside a vessel or tube or that may be clogged by the product.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Both continuous wave and pulsed systems are used.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] The principle behind a pulsed-ultrasonic technology is that the transmit signal consists of short bursts of ultrasonic energy.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] After each burst, the electronics looks for a return signal within a small window of time corresponding to the time it takes for the energy to pass through the vessel.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Only a signal received during this window will qualify for additional signal processing.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] A popular consumer application of ultrasonic ranging was the Polaroid SX-70 camera, which included a lightweight transducer system to focus the camera automatically.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Polaroid later licensed this ultrasound technology and it became the basis of a variety of ultrasonic products.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] A common ultrasound application is an automatic door opener, where an ultrasonic sensor detects a person's approach and opens the door.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Ultrasonic sensors are also used to detect intruders; the ultrasound can cover a wide area from a single point.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] The flow in pipes or open channels can be measured by ultrasonic flowmeters, which measure the average velocity of flowing liquid.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] In rheology, an acoustic rheometer relies on analyzing the propagation of ultrasound to determine a fluid's viscosity.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] In fluid mechanics, fluid flow can be measured using an ultrasonic flow meter based on the Doppler effect.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Ultrasonic testing is a type of nondestructive testing commonly used to find flaws in materials and to measure the thickness of objects.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Frequencies of 2 to 10 MHz are common, but for special purposes other frequencies are used.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Inspection may be manual or automated and is an essential part of modern manufacturing processes.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Most metals can be inspected as well as plastics and aerospace composites.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Lower frequency ultrasound (50–500 kHz) can also be used to inspect less dense materials such as wood, concrete and cement.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Ultrasound inspection of welded joints has been an alternative to radiography for nondestructive testing since the 1960s.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Ultrasonic inspection eliminates the use of ionizing radiation, with safety and cost benefits.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Ultrasound can also provide additional information such as the depth of flaws in a welded joint.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Ultrasonic inspection has progressed from manual methods to computerized systems that automate much of the process.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] An ultrasonic test of a joint can identify the existence of flaws, measure their size, and identify their location.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Not all welded materials are equally amenable to ultrasonic inspection; some materials have a large grain size that produces a high level of background noise in measurements.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Ultrasonic thickness measurement is one technique used to monitor quality of welds.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] A common use of ultrasound is in underwater range finding; this use is also called sonar.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] An ultrasonic pulse is generated in a particular direction.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] If there is an object in the path of this pulse, part or all of the pulse will be reflected back to the transmitter as an echo and can be detected through the receiver path.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] By measuring the difference in time between the pulse being transmitted and the echo being received, it is possible to determine the distance.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] The measured travel time of Sonar pulses in water is strongly dependent on the temperature and the salinity of the water.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Ultrasonic ranging is also applied for measurement in air and for short distances.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] For example, hand-held ultrasonic measuring tools can rapidly measure the layout of rooms.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Although range finding underwater is performed at both sub-audible and audible frequencies for great distances (1 to several kilometers), ultrasonic range finding is used when distances are shorter and the accuracy of the distance measurement is desired to be better.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Ultrasonic measurements may be limited through barrier layers with large salinity, temperature or vortex differences.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Ranging in water varies from about hundreds to thousands of meters, but can be performed with centimeters to meters for accuracy.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] The potential for ultrasonic imaging of objects, in which a 3 GHz sound wave could produce resolution comparable to an optical image, was recognized by Sergei Sokolov in 1939.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Such frequencies were not possible at the time, and what technology did exist produced relatively low-contrast images with poor sensitivity.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Ultrasonic imaging uses frequencies of 2 megahertz and higher; the shorter wavelength allows resolution of small internal details in structures and tissues.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] The power density is generally less than 1 watt per square centimetre to avoid heating and cavitation effects in the object under examination.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Ultrasonic imaging applications include industrial nondestructive testing, quality control and medical uses.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Imaging can be viewed as ranging with added angular information.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Acoustic microscopy is the technique of using sound waves to visualize structures too small to be resolved by the human eye.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] High and ultra high frequencies up to several gigahertz are used in acoustic microscopes.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] The reflection and diffraction of sound waves from microscopic structures can yield information not available with light.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Medical ultrasound is an ultrasound-based diagnostic medical imaging technique used to visualize muscles, tendons, and many internal organs to capture their size, structure and any pathological lesions with real time tomographic images.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Ultrasound has been used by radiologists and sonographers to image the human body for at least 50 years and has become a widely used diagnostic tool.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] The technology is relatively inexpensive and portable, especially when compared with other techniques, such as magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) and computed tomography (CT).
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Ultrasound is also used to visualize fetuses during routine and emergency prenatal care.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Such diagnostic applications used during pregnancy are referred to as obstetric sonography.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Ultrasound is also increasingly being used in trauma and first aid cases, with emergency ultrasound being used by some EMT response teams.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Furthermore, ultrasound is used in remote diagnosis cases where teleconsultation is required, such as scientific experiments in space or mobile sports team diagnosis, as the equipment is more portable compared to other imaging methods.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] According to RadiologyInfo, ultrasounds are useful in the detection of pelvic abnormalities and can involve techniques known as abdominal (transabdominal) ultrasound, vaginal (transvaginal or endovaginal) ultrasound in women, and also rectal (transrectal) ultrasound in men.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] In Doppler ultrasonography, the speed of objects is measured along with their positions.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] This is especially useful for analyzing blood flow in the heart (Doppler echocardiography).
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] As currently applied in the medical field, properly performed ultrasound poses no known risks to the patient.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Sonography does not use ionizing radiation, and the power levels used for imaging are too low to cause adverse heating or pressure effects in tissue.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Although the long-term effects due to ultrasound exposure at diagnostic intensity are still unknown, currently most doctors feel that the benefits to patients outweigh the risks.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Diagnostic ultrasound is used externally in horses for evaluation of soft tissue and tendon injuries, and internally in particular for reproductive work – evaluation of the reproductive tract of the mare and pregnancy detection.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] It may also be used in an external manner in stallions for evaluation of testicular condition and diameter as well as internally for reproductive evaluation (deferent duct etc.).
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] By 2005, ultrasound technology began to be used by the beef cattle industry to improve animal health and the yield of cattle operations.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Ultrasound is used to evaluate fat thickness, rib eye area, and intramuscular fat in living animals.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] It is also used to evaluate the health and characteristics of unborn calves.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Ultrasound technology provides a means for cattle producers to obtain information that can be used to improve the breeding and husbandry of cattle.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] The technology can be expensive, and it requires a substantial time commitment for continuous data collection and operator training.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Nevertheless, this technology has proven useful in managing and running a cattle breeding operation.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] High-power applications of ultrasound often use frequencies between 20 kHz and a few hundred kHz.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Intensities can be very high; above 10 watts per square centimeter, cavitation can be inducted in liquid media, and some applications use up to 1000 watts per square centimeter.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Such high intensities can induce chemical changes or produce significant effects by direct mechanical action, and can inactivate harmful microorganisms.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Ultrasound has been used since the 1940s by physical and occupational therapists for treating connective tissue: ligaments, tendons, and fascia (and also scar tissue).
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Conditions for which ultrasound may be used for treatment include the follow examples: ligament sprains, muscle strains, tendonitis, joint inflammation, plantar fasciitis, metatarsalgia, facet irritation, impingement syndrome, bursitis, rheumatoid arthritis, osteoarthritis, and scar tissue adhesion.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Relatively high power ultrasound can break up stony deposits or tissue, increase skin permeability, accelerate the effect of drugs in a targeted area, assist in the measurement of the elastic properties of tissue, and can be used to sort cells or small particles for research.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Ultrasonic impact treatment (UIT) uses ultrasound to enhance the mechanical and physical properties of metals.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] It is a metallurgical processing technique in which ultrasonic energy is applied to a metal object.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Ultrasonic treatment can result in controlled residual compressive stress, grain refinement and grain size reduction.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Low and high cycle fatigue are enhanced and have been documented to provide increases up to ten times greater than non-UIT specimens.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Additionally, UIT has proven effective in addressing stress corrosion cracking, corrosion fatigue and related issues.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] When the UIT tool, made up of the ultrasonic transducer, pins and other components, comes into contact with the work piece it acoustically couples with the work piece, creating harmonic resonance.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] This harmonic resonance is performed at a carefully calibrated frequency, to which metals respond very favorably.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Depending on the desired effects of treatment a combination of different frequencies and displacement amplitude is applied.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] These frequencies range between 25 and 55 kHz, with the displacement amplitude of the resonant body of between 22 and 50 μm (0.00087 and 0.0020 in).
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] UIT devices rely on magnetostrictive transducers.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Ultrasonication offers great potential in the processing of liquids and slurries, by improving the mixing and chemical reactions in various applications and industries.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Ultrasonication generates alternating low-pressure and high-pressure waves in liquids, leading to the formation and violent collapse of small vacuum bubbles.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] This phenomenon is termed cavitation and causes high speed impinging liquid jets and strong hydrodynamic shear-forces.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] These effects are used for the deagglomeration and milling of micrometre and nanometre-size materials as well as for the disintegration of cells or the mixing of reactants.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] In this aspect, ultrasonication is an alternative to high-speed mixers and agitator bead mills.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Ultrasonic foils under the moving wire in a paper machine will use the shock waves from the imploding bubbles to distribute the cellulose fibres more uniformly in the produced paper web, which will make a stronger paper with more even surfaces.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Furthermore, chemical reactions benefit from the free radicals created by the cavitation as well as from the energy input and the material transfer through boundary layers.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] For many processes, this sonochemical (see sonochemistry) effect leads to a substantial reduction in the reaction time, like in the transesterification of oil into biodiesel.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Substantial ultrasonic intensity and high ultrasonic vibration amplitudes are required for many processing applications, such as nano-crystallization, nano-emulsification, deagglomeration, extraction, cell disruption, as well as many others.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Commonly, a process is first tested on a laboratory scale to prove feasibility and establish some of the required ultrasonic exposure parameters.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] After this phase is complete, the process is transferred to a pilot (bench) scale for flow-through pre-production optimization and then to an industrial scale for continuous production.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] During these scale-up steps, it is essential to make sure that all local exposure conditions (ultrasonic amplitude, cavitation intensity, time spent in the active cavitation zone, etc.) stay the same.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] If this condition is met, the quality of the final product remains at the optimized level, while the productivity is increased by a predictable "scale-up factor".
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] The productivity increase results from the fact that laboratory, bench and industrial-scale ultrasonic processor systems incorporate progressively larger ultrasonic horns, able to generate progressively larger high-intensity cavitation zones and, therefore, to process more material per unit of time.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] It is important to point out that increasing the power of the ultrasonic processor alone does *not* result in direct scalability, since it may be (and frequently is) accompanied by a reduction in the ultrasonic amplitude and cavitation intensity.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] During direct scale-up, all processing conditions must be maintained, while the power rating of the equipment is increased in order to enable the operation of a larger ultrasonic horn.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] A researcher at the Industrial Materials Research Institute, Alessandro Malutta, devised an experiment that demonstrated the trapping action of ultrasonic standing waves on wood pulp fibers diluted in water and their parallel orienting into the equidistant pressure planes.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] The time to orient the fibers in equidistant planes is measured with a laser and an electro-optical sensor.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] This could provide the paper industry a quick on-line fiber size measurement system.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] A somewhat different implementation was demonstrated at Pennsylvania State University using a microchip which generated a pair of perpendicular standing surface acoustic waves allowing to position particles equidistant to each other on a grid.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] This experiment, called acoustic tweezers, can be used for applications in material sciences, biology, physics, chemistry and nanotechnology.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Ultrasonic cleaners, sometimes mistakenly called *supersonic cleaners*, are used at frequencies from 20 to 40 kHz for jewellery, lenses and other optical parts, watches, dental instruments, surgical instruments, diving regulators and industrial parts.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] An ultrasonic cleaner works mostly by energy released from the collapse of millions of microscopic cavitation bubbles near the dirty surface.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] The collapsing bubbles form tiny shockwaves that break up and disperse contaminants on the object's surface.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Similar to ultrasonic cleaning, biological cells including bacteria can be disintegrated.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] High power ultrasound produces cavitation that facilitates particle disintegration or reactions.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] This has uses in biological science for analytical or chemical purposes (sonication and sonoporation) and in killing bacteria in sewage.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] High power ultrasound can disintegrate corn slurry and enhance liquefaction and saccharification for higher ethanol yield in dry corn milling plants.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] The ultrasonic humidifier, one type of nebulizer (a device that creates a very fine spray), is a popular type of humidifier.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] It works by vibrating a metal plate at ultrasonic frequencies to nebulize (sometimes incorrectly called "atomize") the water.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Because the water is not heated for evaporation, it produces a cool mist.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] The ultrasonic pressure waves nebulize not only the water but also materials in the water including calcium, other minerals, viruses, fungi, bacteria, and other impurities.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Illness caused by impurities that reside in a humidifier's reservoir fall under the heading of "Humidifier Fever".
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Ultrasonic humidifiers are frequently used in aeroponics, where they are generally referred to as foggers.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] In ultrasonic welding of plastics, high frequency (15 kHz to 40 kHz) low amplitude vibration is used to create heat by way of friction between the materials to be joined.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] The interface of the two parts is specially designed to concentrate the energy for maximum weld strength.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Power ultrasound in the 20–100 kHz range is used in chemistry.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] The ultrasound does not interact directly with molecules to induce the chemical change, as its typical wavelength (in the millimeter range) is too long compared to the molecules.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Instead, the energy causes cavitation which generates extremes of temperature and pressure in the liquid where the reaction happens.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Ultrasound also breaks up solids and removes passivating layers of inert material to give a larger surface area for the reaction to occur over.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Both of these effects make the reaction faster.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] In 2008, Atul Kumar reported synthesis of Hantzsch esters and polyhydroquinoline derivatives via multi-component reaction protocol in aqueous micelles using ultrasound.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Ultrasound is used in extraction, using different frequencies.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] When applied in specific configurations, ultrasound can produce short bursts of light in a phenomenon known as sonoluminescence.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Ultrasound is used when characterizing particulates through the technique of ultrasound attenuation spectroscopy or by observing electroacoustic phenomena or by transcranial pulsed ultrasound.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Audio can be propagated by modulated ultrasound.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] A formerly popular consumer application of ultrasound was in television remote controls for adjusting volume and changing channels.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Introduced by Zenith in the late 1950s, the system used a hand-held remote control containing short rod resonators struck by small hammers, and a microphone on the set.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Filters and detectors discriminated between the various operations.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] The principal advantages were that no battery was needed in the hand-held control box and, unlike radio waves, the ultrasound was unlikely to affect neighboring sets.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Ultrasound remained in use until displaced by infrared systems starting in the late 1980s.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] In July 2015, *The Economist* reported that researchers at the University of California, Berkeley have conducted ultrasound studies using graphene diaphragms.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] The thinness and low weight of graphene combined with its strength make it an effective material to use in ultrasound communications.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] One suggested application of the technology would be underwater communications, where radio waves typically do not travel well.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Ultrasonic signals have been used in "audio beacons" for cross-device tracking of Internet users.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Occupational exposure to ultrasound in excess of 120 dB may lead to hearing loss.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] Exposure in excess of 155 dB may produce heating effects that are harmful to the human body, and it has been calculated that exposures above 180 dB may lead to death.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] The UK's independent Advisory Group on Non-ionising Radiation (AGNIR) produced a report in 2010, which was published by the UK Health Protection Agency (HPA).
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] This report recommended an exposure limit for the general public to airborne ultrasound sound pressure levels (SPL) of 70 dB (at 20 kHz), and 100 dB (at 25 kHz and above).
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] In medical ultrasound, guidelines exist to prevent inertial cavitation from happening.
[src:ultrasound-imaging/ultrasound] The risk of inertial cavitation damage is expressed by the mechanical index.
